WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.720
Hello, thank you everyone for being here today. I know there were a lot of good talks in this

00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:09.680
time slot, so I really appreciate you coming to this one. I'm Christine, and today I'm going to

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:16.080
tell you kind of a data fairy tale of sorts. And it starts on not a dark and stormy night,

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:23.360
but just a regular day in the day of a data wrangler and sometime last fall. And I'm like

00:00:23.360 --> 00:00:28.160
doing some regular work and drinking some microwaved coffee that's now cold. And I get

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:33.520
this email from a work colleague asking if I could take a call with the White House today.

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:41.119
And I immediately had some imposter syndrome as I'm in the pocket office in the basement of my

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:46.799
rural main home, wondering how this could be happening. And before I knew it, I was in fact

00:00:46.799 --> 00:00:51.919
on a call with the White House that afternoon, informing them that they probably underestimated

00:00:52.799 --> 00:01:00.000
how much funding would be needed to get the Affordable Care Connectivity Program through

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.439
the end of 2024. And I'll explain in just a minute what that program is.

00:01:04.959 --> 00:01:09.760
So it was a very weird situation to be in. And you might be wondering, like, Christine,

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:15.360
how did you find yourself in this moment? And it's because of this dashboard we built.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:21.279
No, this isn't going to be a talk about how to build a dashboard. There are many excellent talks

00:01:21.279 --> 00:01:27.440
about that that I've seen this week and they're online. Rather, this is going to be a talk about

00:01:28.320 --> 00:01:36.080
how you can take or how you should take whatever data viz tool thing that you are making and how

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:43.519
to make it as impactful as possible. And we're going to rewind time a little bit further back

00:01:43.519 --> 00:01:49.519
to 2021. So the pandemic is still hanging on. People are isolated, quarantining,

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:55.760
and it's never been more apparent around the world how important it is to be able to get

00:01:55.760 --> 00:02:02.559
online to access the Internet. And in the U.S., the Federal Communications Commission, which is

00:02:02.559 --> 00:02:09.199
the government entity responsible for all things telecommunications, including the Internet,

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:14.559
recognized that a lot of people couldn't afford to get online. And this was a big problem because

00:02:14.559 --> 00:02:18.320
at this point, we're still, you know, a lot of people are working remotely, they're schooling

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:24.639
remotely, telehealth is a rising technology. And so for folks not to be able to afford to get

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:28.720
online was an issue. And so they started the Affordable Connectivity Program, which had a

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:37.919
bank account of $14.2 billion. And it didn't have a timeline for when it would end because it felt

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:44.880
like a very kind of a pandemic-centric program. But it also had no plan for when more money would

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:49.039
be added. There were a lot of questions about this program, but they got it stood up quickly

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:55.839
and helped a lot of people afford their Internet bill each month. It gave them a $30 discount for

00:02:55.839 --> 00:03:02.639
eligible household unless you lived in tribal lands, and then it was $75. Now, because this was

00:03:02.639 --> 00:03:10.320
a federal program, the enrollment and claims data, so how much was being spent and like how many

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:16.960
people were enrolling, was made publicly available. But much like A Princess in the Tower, the data

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:22.880
were technically available, but they weren't really accessible. And what I mean by that is there were

00:03:23.919 --> 00:03:29.759
national data in a web table, there were more national data in little web tables on a separate

00:03:29.759 --> 00:03:35.440
web page, and then this whole list of spreadsheets that were split up by geography and year.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.160
So for any given person to be curious about what enrollment rates looked like

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:44.960
in their community, they would have to somehow navigate all this. And also all these different

00:03:45.600 --> 00:03:51.679
data sets were updated on different update schedules. So you also had to keep that in

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:58.479
mind as you're navigating all this. And around this time, as things are kind of getting going

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:03.119
with the program, I started to get a lot of questions about, you know, what is enrollment like

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:08.479
in Cleveland or LA or New York State? And initially I was kind of doing these like one-of

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:14.240
things, and then it started to become like majority of my job. And I thought, perhaps this is a great

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:20.000
time to figure out how to build a dashboard. I was still kind of new in my like data science job.

00:04:20.559 --> 00:04:29.279
And at the time, I was very proficient in data wrangling in R. But then when I thought about

00:04:29.279 --> 00:04:34.880
trying to create a dashboard in R, it gave me a bit of anxiety. I don't know how to use Shiny

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:39.920
yet. It's part of my learning plan for this year, and I'm very excited to learn Quarto. But

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:45.760
at that time, those things weren't accessible to me. We did have some experience on the team

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:50.320
working with Tableau, which is like another data visualization tool. And I had played around with

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:56.880
it a little. So we decided to use that. So we combined data wrangling in R and then visualized

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:03.359
those elements that we created in Tableau. And so this is my first point. And I've seen this in other

00:05:03.359 --> 00:05:08.720
talks this week, and I think it's a really, it's simple, but you know, use what is available and

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:14.559
accessible to you now. It's fine if you have the time and bandwidth to learn that new tool,

00:05:14.559 --> 00:05:19.440
learn Quarto and Shiny and other like really cool things that are out there. But if you don't have

00:05:19.440 --> 00:05:25.359
the bandwidth, make a plan to learn it later. You don't have to do it now. Give yourself a break.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:32.559
Since we decided on that plan, we first had to like clean up all this data. It was really a hot

00:05:32.559 --> 00:05:38.160
mess. If anyone's played with federal data, you can probably attest to this. Even state data,

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:43.119
really. And so this is just like a tiny little clip from one of the spreadsheets. And you can

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:49.200
see on the far right, well, each record is supposed to be a single state line, but we've got data

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:55.600
grouped under a header indicating month and year on the far right. So we had to like pull out all

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.959
this header data to create additional fields and, you know, clean up all the field names and

00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:09.519
just a lot of like labor going into like getting these data into a usable, workable state. And

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:15.200
Tidyverse has been, you know, I'm a big fan of Tidyverse. So like all the tools, underlying

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:21.839
tools and functions in there did a lot of the hefty heavy lifting here. And for anyone that's

00:06:21.839 --> 00:06:31.440
involved in like spatial data wrangling in here, this was something that was new to me and it was

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:38.799
a very big pain. But as I had gotten the data cleaned up and I was joining it with another

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:44.559
set of data, I found that for these nine states, for some reason it wasn't working, but this is

00:06:44.559 --> 00:06:51.760
one of those unfortunate errors in R that is not giving you an error. So you don't necessarily

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:56.799
know what's happening until you see like this weirdness where you have NAs occurring. And it's

00:06:56.799 --> 00:07:01.519
because of, in the left-hand column, you'll see each of those states, the ID number starts with

00:07:01.519 --> 00:07:08.239
a zero. These leading zeros tend to get gobbled up in Excel files and that was causing the mismatch.

00:07:08.239 --> 00:07:12.799
So it was really frustrating. But once I figured it out, I also found this neat little function

00:07:12.799 --> 00:07:19.119
in Stringer that allowed me to say, you know, all these ideas should have two digits and where they

00:07:19.119 --> 00:07:26.480
don't had the left side with a zero. And it was like magic. But ultimately we didn't do anything

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:33.600
magical in this dashboard as a whole. And you'll see it along the way, but it's a lot of just sums,

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:39.839
totals of data. We had one linear model that was like the fanciest thing we had in here. And this

00:07:39.839 --> 00:07:44.480
is my next point. When you're creating these things, it doesn't need to be super fancy. You

00:07:44.480 --> 00:07:50.720
want to keep your end user in mind and what they will need it for and what, how they can use it.

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:54.959
You want it to be something that is accessible to them without you having to go in and explain

00:07:54.959 --> 00:08:02.880
it every time. That will make it more easily shareable. And then next, once we had all of

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:10.320
our data cleaned up and put together, we started to work on our eligibility estimate. So in order

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:16.399
to calculate enrollment rates across the country, we had to determine how many people were actually

00:08:16.399 --> 00:08:22.559
eligible for this program. So we used tidy census to pull in data from the American Community Survey

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:28.799
and using the guidelines from the FCC for which households were eligible, we came up with this

00:08:29.760 --> 00:08:37.599
kind of basic calculation. From there, we, you know, as the lone data person on my team,

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:43.840
I often work in isolation, but in this situation, this was intended to be a very

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:50.080
like public facing tool. And I really needed feedback on what I'd done so far and how I had

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:55.679
worked with the data, things I had done. And so we started reaching out to anyone that we heard

00:08:55.760 --> 00:09:00.559
had been working with this data set. And so it included other advocacy groups like ourselves,

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:10.479
other research teams, academic folks, whoever we could get a meeting with. And we shared with them

00:09:10.479 --> 00:09:15.919
how we came up with this and this eligibility estimate, ultimately for any folks creating

00:09:15.919 --> 00:09:21.119
tools like this became like the secret sauce. So it was really exciting that people were

00:09:21.919 --> 00:09:28.479
actually welcoming us to talk with them and give us like insights to how they calculated their

00:09:28.479 --> 00:09:34.479
eligibility estimates. And so we, we were able to take those insights back and improve our

00:09:34.479 --> 00:09:40.559
calculation and make it much more robust. And this is my next point. I know a lot of us work

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:45.679
in isolation and I know I've talked with people about it this week, but think about how nice it

00:09:45.679 --> 00:09:51.599
feels to be here this week and talking about data issues and package things this week. Like

00:09:51.599 --> 00:09:56.719
it feels really good and you get such good feedback on things. So keep that in mind as

00:09:56.719 --> 00:10:01.520
you're working on these data products. It can only really make it better ultimately.

00:10:03.520 --> 00:10:06.799
And so finally we had all of this information put together.

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:17.840
We put it into Tableau, fine-tuned and published it. We have, and we, you know,

00:10:18.400 --> 00:10:22.719
we didn't stop there though. Once you get something online, you should never just stop there

00:10:22.719 --> 00:10:26.960
because it's ultimately a tool. It's not going to get itself in front of people's eyes.

00:10:27.679 --> 00:10:33.599
So there's a lot left to be done from here. And we had a few natural avenues that allow us to do

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:39.919
this. So we have a couple of podcasts. Our team has a website. We also have an overarching org

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:48.880
website. So we wrote up an article on our page about the dashboard. It also included the GitHub

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:54.640
where we have all the cleaned up data as well as the code that I use to calculate all these

00:10:54.640 --> 00:11:00.320
different elements. And that went out, this article was sent through all of our listservs,

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:06.080
all of the collaborators that we had previously worked with. We, in some cases, met with them

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:10.880
again and walked through the dashboard and asked for feedback on all the different elements. Like,

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:14.960
is there anything weird here? Is there something that's like not intuitive or not working?

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:24.400
And we got a lot of good feedback and requests for more things. And so not too long after we

00:11:25.359 --> 00:11:31.440
had a huge, like a major update and conveniently following this major update, we were all attending

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:37.440
a big national conference where we printed off these little postcard sized handouts of the

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:42.080
dashboard and had a little info in the back. But we had like a booth just like this conference.

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:48.479
And ACP, this program was a big topic at the conference. There were whole sessions dedicated

00:11:48.479 --> 00:11:52.400
to it. So it came up a lot. And anytime someone would stop by to talk to us,

00:11:53.359 --> 00:11:58.400
and that would come up, have you heard of our dashboard? And so we would hand them the postcard

00:11:58.400 --> 00:12:03.440
and we would explain to them what is in the dashboard and how it can be useful to them.

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:10.239
And so it was a lot of like this word of mouth in person networking, networking with the dashboard

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:18.239
and kind of the central train here is like, just keep talking about it all the time. In fact,

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:25.280
my husband at one point, jokingly kind of banned the word dashboard in our house for

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:29.440
over the time because it was a constant in my life for quite a while.

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:42.239
And unfortunately, this fairy tale kind of has a bittersweet end. Congress did not reallocate

00:12:42.239 --> 00:12:49.200
funding for the program. And so as of June of this year, the program ended and 23 million

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:54.400
or more households lost that financial assistance to be able to get online.

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:01.520
And you might be wondering, well, Christine, like how successful really was this dashboard then?

00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:06.400
And it was really successful because we that was not our intention. Our intention was not

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:12.320
to support this program and keep it going. Our intention with this dashboard and our users

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:19.440
were other advocacy groups from folks that are doing research and more policy advocacy to folks

00:13:19.440 --> 00:13:25.280
on the ground that are actually trying to enroll people in the dashboard. We have a zip code map

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:30.880
and we can hand this to people and say, you know, in your city, these zip codes have really low

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:37.119
enrollment rates. This is where you should spend your limited time, funds, people effort on getting

00:13:37.119 --> 00:13:42.960
people enrolled there. And so in that way, it was super effective. We were also cited in letters

00:13:42.960 --> 00:13:49.760
between congressional members trying to get the program refunded, Senate hearings, academic

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:58.559
literature, a few state digital equity plans or proposals for federal funding. So it was really

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:08.880
impactful in the ways that we had hoped. And just to kind of wrap up and remind you of the things

00:14:08.880 --> 00:14:14.559
that you can do to make sure that your tool is really impactful. Again, use the things that are

00:14:14.559 --> 00:14:19.200
available and accessible to you now, unless you really want to like learn that new thing along the

00:14:19.200 --> 00:14:25.280
way. If not, you can always use the thing that you do create and use that as a template. Now I have

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:31.440
this dashboard, I can use it as a template for when I want to create in Quarto. When you're

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:39.119
designing the dashboard itself, make sure or other tools, make sure you keep in mind the audience and

00:14:39.119 --> 00:14:49.119
their use case. Having like a lot of like intense information and all the possible widgets is not

00:14:49.119 --> 00:14:55.039
necessarily what your end users need. They need the information that can help them do their best work.

00:14:55.679 --> 00:15:01.599
So keep it simple. Collaborate, make sure you're reaching out to other folks in the space,

00:15:03.119 --> 00:15:09.119
sharing information with them, asking questions, improving, getting feedback to improve your work.

00:15:09.119 --> 00:15:13.520
And finally, make sure you're getting it out there. Now I shared some ways that we went about it.

00:15:14.239 --> 00:15:20.880
Another idea is to, you know, kind of do some like cold emails. If you know of people that are

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:26.880
like reporting regularly on a particular topic that you're working on, you can reach out to them

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:32.719
and say, hey, I noticed you report on this a lot. We created this thing. And if you ever need a

00:15:32.719 --> 00:15:37.520
subject matter expert or want to talk about this thing we created, you know, I'm available. It'd be

00:15:37.520 --> 00:15:43.760
great to meet up. That's another way you can kind of get your product out there and in front of more

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:50.960
eyes. It's another outreach opportunity. And finally, I just want to thank you all again.

00:15:51.599 --> 00:15:56.799
I really appreciate being here. And if you want to check out the dashboard, it's at acpdashboard.com.

00:15:56.799 --> 00:16:02.640
That's my final tip. Come up with a great URL. And that's also like really handy.

00:16:04.640 --> 00:16:07.280
And thank you. Happy to take any questions if there's time.

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:15.840
Thank you so much. And we do have time for a few questions. The first one is,

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:21.679
how did you get involved with this type of work? Good question. So my background was actually in

00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:29.520
ecology. I studied birds, but I really enjoyed the spatial data work. And so my focus is on

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:34.880
internet access. And there's a lot of internet data that's inherently spatial, geographic.

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:41.760
And I focused on my job search on GIS and data work. That's how I got here. Awesome.

00:16:43.520 --> 00:16:48.000
And in addition to tidy, what other data wrangling or data cleaning packages do you use?

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:56.400
Janitor, the clean names function is one of my favorites. Anyone else? Yes.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:03.280
I have some fans. I think you answered where the dashboard is hosted.

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:08.479
And with government data, what is your process for like data imputation for missing data and

00:17:08.479 --> 00:17:15.839
things like that? That is a tough one. Because in this data set, and I didn't touch on this,

00:17:15.839 --> 00:17:22.640
but they did redact data in some places where they have to kind of ensure that like privacy

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:26.640
for folks where there's like very few or like limited population sizes.

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:32.560
And that's, it's kind of tough. And it kind of depends on what we're doing. In some cases, it's,

00:17:34.079 --> 00:17:38.800
we include like an asterisk or some like explanation that, you know, in cases,

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:42.560
in some cases, there's going to be missing data. And we just, you know, are upfront about it,

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:47.920
like, and explain like, they redact these data. And so these are not available. It doesn't mean

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:53.599
there isn't something happening here, but we're not inferring what we don't know, really.

00:17:53.599 --> 00:17:58.239
And although funding for the program ended this year, do you know if there's a push to refund the

00:17:58.239 --> 00:18:04.560
program in the future or now? I have heard some rumors. They are still trying to get it through

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:11.680
somehow. While I think it would be great, I'm not entirely optimistic, just because of the way

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:17.199
Congress is kind of going right now. Fair enough. Well, I think that's all the questions that we

00:18:17.199 --> 00:18:21.520
have for now. So I'll go ahead, give it up for Christine. Thank you.

